<page_title>Molecular crystals: packing up molecules</page_title>
<text>Molecular crystals: packing up molecules
p. 2 of 7

&lt; Index | Next &gt;

Molecular crystals are formed by one or more kind of molecules tiled up in the microscopic space with regular patterns. 

 
 * 

The above model shows a crystal formed by A3B8 at 100 K. The green particles represent A and the white ones represent B.
1. Run the model, and then raise the temperature, one tick (marker) at a time.
2. Take a snapshot when you see &quot;melting&quot; and then continue to run the model until you achieve complete melting.  Take another snapshot.    

 At what temperature does it appear to melt?  What is the first sign of melting?

 

 After the molecular crystal is molten, try lowering the temperature to see if you can get it recrystallized. Did you succeed? Take a   of your best effort. Compare this with the easy recrystallization of a non-molecular crystal formed by a simple material.   
*K=Kelvin, a temperature scale with an absolute zero.
